<LP>
   CORPORATE MERGERS can be dismantled by federal courts
through antitrust suits by states or private citizens, the
Supreme Court ruled. The decision, clearing the way for
California to challenge the merger of supermarket chains
Lucky Stores and American Stores, raises the risks for
companies involved in mergers.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Personal spending rose 0.4% in March, mainly because
consumers paid higher prices to keep up with inflation.
Personal income jumped 0.8%, but much of that stemmed from a
boost in farmer subsidies.
                                                                                                       

   Inflation worries are rising among economists, in part
because the Fed is under pressure to avoid moves that might
hurt the economic expansion.
   ---
   Bank and thrift failures in New England could surge in the
next few years, surpassing the more than dozen insolvencies
of the past two decades, analysts and regulators say.
   ---
   A major program trader, Susquehanna Investment, was fined
$170,000 by the CBOE for alleged abusive trading in stocks
and stock options. The fine is part of a crackdown on alleged
intermarket abuses.
   ---
   Ashton-Tate's chairman and chief executive, Edward Esber,
resigned from the troubled PC-software maker. Executives said
the firm may be for sale, but an official denied it.
   ---
   Union Texas Petroleum is seeking a buyer, and analysts say
the company could fetch up to $2 billion. Union Texas is
controlled by Kohlberg Kravis and Allied-Signal.
   ---
   Donald Trump's Taj Mahal casino had a strong first month
of operation, but his two other Atlantic City casinos appear
to have suffered as a result, unaudited early tallies
indicate.
   ---
   IBM expects a "substantially improved" performance this
year and sees a "very bright" future, Chairman John Akers
told the annual meeting. The more positive tone sent IBM's
stock up $1.625, to $109.
   ---
   Torchmark was ordered by Tennessee regulators to halt its
proxy battle with American General. But Torchmark plans a
legal challenge.
   ---
   Boeing's profit plunged 34% in the first quarter, though
operating earnings surged 87%. As expected, the aerospace
giant boosted its dividend and split its stock three-for-two.
   ---
   Armstrong World Industries said it won at least three of
the four board seats contested by Canada's Belzberg family,
which has been mulling a bid for the company. The final tally
isn't expected until at least May 11.
   ---
   GM was dealt a blow in the Supreme Court, which let stand
a ruling allowing ex-workers to sue GM for refusing to
consider rehiring them.
   ---
   Ames Department Stores hired retailing consultant Stephen
Pistner to rescue the discount chain from the financial woes
of its Zayre stores.
   ---
   PepsiCo's profit rose 10% in the first quarter despite
continued expenses from previous acquisitions. Operating
earnings jumped 22%.
